					<h2 class="text">Actually responsive</h3>
					<p class="lede text">Is 'responsive design' just 'designing for all screen types'? I believe 'responsive' means much more. It means designing and building websites that respond to the user: who they are, what they need to achieve.</p>
					 <p class="text">I start every project by getting to know your users. Here, I drew up detailed User Case Studies, drawn from various sources: discussion with the client, who knew their customer better than anybody else; detailed analysis of existing (or competitor) analytics, and structured interviews with key stakeholders.</p>
					<p class="text">Once I've mapped who your users are, what they need, and what you need them to do, we can design something bespoke for them. That means a) sites that work for your intended audience, b) market-leading conversion rates, and c) unparallelled user experience.</p>
					<p class="text">Here, we separated the key user groups – Exhibitors and Visitors – from subsidiary user groups (such as Contractors). Each of the two main groups can filter out irrelevant information, which cuts scrolling (especially on mobile devices) and lowers the tendency for on-page information to compete for a user's limited attention. Information relevant to each user group is colour-coordinated: again, providing users with clear, instruction-rich routes to achieving their aims as quickly as possible.</p>

					<h2 class="text">Cutting-edge technology that gracefully degrades</h2>
					<p class="lede text">Wouldn't it be great if you could leave a project safe in the knowledge it'll work from here to the end of time? A lot of clients ask me about 'future-proofing'. No-one wants a site that looks and feels outdated within a year of being delivered. On the other hand, no-one wants a site that only programmers can view on their specced-up, Chrome-running supercomputers. I select technologies which meet all these needs.</p>
					<p class="text">Here, I've built a high-performance <a href="rubyonrails.org">Ruby on Rails</a> <abbr title="Application Programming Interface">API</abbr> that serves content from an ultra-secure <a href="http://www.postgresql.org/">PostgreSQL</a> database. This means the client can use their content – bookings, news articles, exhibitor lists, and so much more – in a whole range of ways, all from a single place. The website is built using the <a href="emberjs.org">EmberJS</a> JavaScript framework, which means a) no page loads (critical for rural connections), b) high cross-browser consistency, and c) excellent support for 'legacy' browsers such as <abbr title="Internet Explorer">IE</abbr>7. That last point is especially important for the target user, who often uses an older browser.</p>
					<p class="text">Content is administrated from a custom <abbr title="Content Management System">CMS</abbr>, and instantly available through the API. The CMS includes deep analytics integration through <a href="http://www.mixpanel.com">MixPanel</a>, and a custom dashboard that updates live as transactions happen elsewhere. It's a command centre for the whole Livestock Event: anyone can get an overview of the entire business at a glance. There's an intelligent notification system that lets RABDF employees know when action needs to happen, a tile-builder for adding and editing content on the site, and deep search and model management features that have enabled RABDF to replace their existing <abbr title="Customer Relationship Management">CRM</abbr> system.</p>
					<p class="text">What about maintainability? Most web code is pretty easy to understand, if you have the right background. If you don't, what then? There's nothing worse than being delivered an intractable mess of vermicelli code. Aside from commenting everything I write, I include a Developer Guide to extending and maintaining whatever I deliver. That way, you're free to go wherever suits you best.</p>

					<h2 class="text">Surprise and Delight</h2>
					<p class="text">Great <abbr title="User Experience">UX</abbr> is about more than usability. Making a site that structures content in a clear, accessible and minimal way is only half the story: great sites are <i>pleasurable</i> – <a href="http://www.slideshare.net/stephenpa/creating-pleasurable-interfaces-getting-from-tasks-to-experiences">even <i>meaningful</i></a> – to those who use them.</p>
					<p class="text">Sometimes pleasure and usability coincide. For example, I've used <abbr title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr> animations to convey relationships between information. Here's an example: some 'tiles' can be flipped to reveal additional content. No page loads – no drop-off – but no skimping on info, either.</p>
